news.title: Evergrande: China's fragile housing giant
news.para: Any possible bankruptcy of the group -- which claims to employ 200,000 people and indirectly generate 3.8 million jobs in China -- would have major repercussions on the country's economy, and possibly the world.

news.title: Ireland announces multibillion euro plan to fix housing crisis
news.para: The plan, which includes a guarantee of 20 billion euros ($24 billion) of state funding over the first five years, is aimed at increasing homebuilding to an average of 33,000 units per year by 2030 from around 20,000 last year.

news.title: New Zealand's central bank seeks tougher mortgage rules ahead of rate decision
news.para: Investors have continued to buy properties, buoyed by historically low interest rates and cheap access to finance from the government's pandemic stimulus spending.

news.title: Ahmedabad civic body launches single-window TDR clearance for heritage homes
news.para: The committee was also informed that 13 listed heritage buildings have been demolished while 230 heritage homes are yet to tagged with special heritage plates.

news.title: Greater Noida authority imposes fine on four builders for violating NGT norms
news.para: A penalty of Rs 50,000 was levied on Anand Builder and Moni Construction Company. A fine of Rs 1 lakh was imposed on the Apex Alphabet and French Apartments.

news.title: Kolhapur: Construction at Bramhapuri hill without ASI permission
news.para: Social activists from the Bhrashtachar Virodhi Janshakti party have written to Ravikant Adsul, the deputy commissioner of Kolhapur Municipal Corporation, to stop the construction activities immediately.

news.title: Tamil Nadu: New bill allows registrars to cancel a forged property document
news.para: ​​According to the State Amendment Bill to the Registration Act, 1908, (a Central legislation), a registering officer shall refuse to register a forged document.

news.title: Pune: PMPML board gives nod to commercialise land parcels
news.para: “The idea is to use the PMPML’s land for commercial purposes based on the market demand in that particular area and the business potential,” said Chetna Kerure, the joint managing director of the PMPML.

news.title: Lucknow civic body extends deadline, now pay property tax by September 30
news.para: The decision was taken by mayor Sanyukta Bhatia to provide relief to families affected due to Covid-19. According to officials, LMC gives concession of up to 10% till August 31 every year.

news.title: Indiabulls Housing Finance to raise Rs 1,000 crore
news.para: At least 75% of the funds raised through this Tranche I Issue will be used for the purpose of onward lending, financing, and for repayment of interest and principal of existing borrowings of the company.

news.title: Financial relief for owners without lease deeds in Jaipur
news.para: Decision has been taken to exempt fines and interest imposed on regularisation charges on owners who do not have lease deeds (patta) of their plots/houses.

news.title: About 1.5 lakh Amrapali buyers await SC ruling to pave way for registry
news.para: The hearing is on the review petition filed by the authority in respect to an earlier decision regarding the interest dispute part in the matter filed by Ace Group.

news.title: We paid for parks, upkeep is our right: RWAs to Gurgaon civic body commissioner
news.para: Moreover, the representatives also appealed to the commissioner for involvement of RWAs in the development work done by MCG in the respective sectors.

news.title: Rajasthan: Relief for residents who failed to carry out construction on purchased plots
news.para: An official said people who purchase plots through auction or lottery have to carry out minimum construction in the vacant plot in a stipulated time.

news.title: Construction sites not using dust screens under Nashik civic body scanner
news.para: In January last year, the NMC had made use of dust screens mandatory for construction sites in order to curb air pollution in the city. Initially, the dust screens were used by the builders at construction sites, but gradually a section of builders allegedly started violating the rule.
